The paper deals with interference management in a network setting, which is a classic topic in information theory (cs.IT). The focus is on networks with no channel state information at the transmitter (CSIT), which is a subfield of interference alignment (cs.NI). The paper proposes achievability schemes based on graph coloring, interference alignment, and hypergraph covering, which are common techniques in network information theory (cs.SI). The paper also discusses the concept of compound channel settings, which is related to multi-user communication (cs.MM). Finally, the paper uses the concept of index coding to analyze the achievable degrees of freedom, which is a topic in graph theory (cs.GT).
